SIMPLE: fray
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: fray
<hw>fray</hw> <pr>(fr⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbreviated from
<ets>affray</ets>.]</ety> <def>An angry quarrel; an affray; contest;
combat; broil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who began this bloody <qex>fray</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fray
<hw>Fray</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Frayed</conjf> <pr>(fr⟦amac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fraying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See 1st <er>Fray</er>, and cf.
<er>Affray</er>.]</ety> <def>To frighten; to terrify; to alarm.</def>
<rj><au>I. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>frays</qex> ye, that were wont to comfort me
affrayed?</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fray
<hw>Fray</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>fraier</ets>. See
<er>Defray</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>To bear the expense of; to
defray.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The charge of my most curious and costly ingredients
<qex>frayed</qex>, I shall acknowledge myself amply satisfied.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fray
<hw>Fray</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>freier</ets>,
<ets>fraier</ets>, <ets>froier</ets>, to rub. L. <ets>fricare</ets>; cf.
<ets>friare</ets> to crumble, E. <ets>friable</ets>; perh. akin to Gr.
<grk>chri`ein</grk> to anoint, <grk>chri^sma</grk> an anointing, Skr.
<ets>gh⟦rsdot⟧sh</ets> to rub, scratch. Cf. <er>Friction</er>.]</ety>
<def>To rub; to wear off, or wear into shreds, by rubbing; to fret, as
cloth; <as>as, a deer is said to <ex>fray</ex> her head</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fray
<hw>Fray</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rub.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We can show the marks he made⟦br⟧
When 'gainst the oak his antlers <qex>frayed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wear out or into shreads, or to suffer injury by
rubbing, as when the threads of the warp or of the woof wear off so that
the cross threads are loose; to ravel; <as>as, the cloth <ex>frays</ex>
badly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A suit of <qex>frayed</qex> magnificience.</q>
<rj><qau>tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Fray
<hw>Fray</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fret or chafe, as in cloth; a place
injured by rubbing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fraying</ent>⟦br⟧
